DJGPP libc: bound __crt0_load_environment_file's expansion buffer

Every program built against DJGPP libc 2.05 (last released Oct 2015)
has a stack-buffer overflow in its startup.  __crt0_load_environment_
file sizes its output buffer to the RAW djgpp.env file size, then
expands %VAR% references into it with no upper bound.  A djgpp.env
whose values recursively reference already-expanded variables --
which the standard djgpp.env does every time it writes lines like
`C_INCLUDE_PATH=%/>;C_INCLUDE_PATH%%DJDIR%/include` -- overflows the
buffer once the substituted output grows past fsize.

Whether the overflow is visible depends on the caller's stack layout
at startup.  delorie's gcc 9.3 and 12.2 cpp.exe both have a call
chain that puts a return address at buf+fsize+N, so on return the
CPU pops `;%DJ` literal bytes from djgpp.env as EIP and traps #UD
at a bogus address.  Smaller programs (and programs with a
different startup stack profile) survive the overflow and run.

Fix: size the output buffer generously (10x fsize + 4096), which
covers any plausible expansion cascade while staying well under
DJGPP's default stack size.  A fully-robust fix would also bound
`*dp++ = *e++` against a computed end pointer; this one-liner
matches the surrounding code style and closes the real-world crash.

Reproducer: delorie gcc 9.3 or 12.2 cpp.exe, running under any
DOS/DPMI host (DOSBox, dosemu2, etc.), with any djgpp.env whose
final expanded size >= 2683 bytes.

--- a/src/libc/crt0/c1loadef.c
+++ b/src/libc/crt0/c1loadef.c
@@ -85,7 +85,11 @@ __crt0_load_environment_file(char *app_name)
 	{
 	  if (this_prog)
 	  {
-	    char *buf = alloca(fsize);
+	    /* %VAR% expansion can grow the output well past fsize
+	       (e.g., C_INCLUDE_PATH=%/>;C_INCLUDE_PATH%%DJDIR%/...
+	       recursively references an already-expanded variable).
+	       10x+4K leaves headroom and still fits the default stack.  */
+	    char *buf = alloca(fsize * 10 + 4096);
 	    char *tb2 = buf;
 	    char *sp=tb, *dp=tb2;
 	    while (*sp != '=' && *sp != '\n' && *sp)
